item.title: It's interesting to look at the trends in inconsistency..
item.description:
Many pro lifers and aren't pro life when the baby needs food or healthcare, they're pro birth in that they want to control what women can do with their bodies. Likewise a lot of people are concerned with the exploitation of women when it comes to sex work, but not people's exploitation throughout the countless other work fields that exploit labor's mental, physical, and emotional health. It's also interesting how many people I see online hate on OF but not the porn industry as a whole. OF tends to give women more control than the old porn industry did but people act like it's causing society to fall apart. It's like for some people society being stable is synonymous with women not having full bodily autonomy and instead needing to have some portion of their decision making involving their own body controlled by others; and also a a labor class who's exploitation is ignored. I think part of the reason porn bothers some people so much is because it is a rebellion against many oppressive systems, and OF is more of a rebellion than the old porn industry, though it still operated within capitalism, and thus comes with those limits and flaws https://www.instagram.com/prosperdoesthings
Oh, one more topic, "self objectification". I see people some times call people creating sexy content of themselves, self objectification, but that's a misunderstanding of the term. The core of objectifying is about agency, objects don't have agency, human beings do. If someone decides to pose in a sexy way, they are exercising agency, not objectifying themselves. Now if someone sees a person posing and thinks, "People like that are only good for one thing, me to fuck", that is getting tunnel vision on one facet of someone and how they can be used for your desires. I like Immanuel Kant’s "Formula of Humanity" part of which dictates that rational beings must never be treated merely as a means to an end, but always as ends in themselves. I will say this gets a little complicated and I even disagree with some "scientific" studies on the topic. The problem I see, is that a picture of a person is in fact an object not a person, it's a picture of a person. There's studies that show men look longer at a woman's body than face when she's in sexy outfits vs modest outfits, but these are pictures not people so the men aren't trying to read the woman's emotional state changes, or how she's reacting to them reacting to her, since it's a static image, that doesn't react or change, not a person but an object. There are cases were it is clear the person in the picture is having the agency ignored, for example up skit pictures taken without the person's consent, and though the image of that is itself is an object not a person, looking at it still violates someone else's agency and if willfully looked at it is objectifying them by participating in the ignoring of their agency. There's obviously a lot more that could be said on this topic, but that's just a quick over on the idea of self objectification.
